  "text": "We consider a growth model\u00e0 la Solow [CITATION_1] in which there exists a delay of periods before capital becomes productive after the investment. This implies that, at time , the productive capital stock is ( \u2212 ). By assuming a Cobb-Douglas technology, we have that the total income at time is ( ) = ( \u2212 ) ( ) 1\u2212 , where ( ) represents labor force at time and \u2208 (0, 1) is the capital's share. Departing from Zak [CITATION_2] we assume that population grows at a constant rate \u0338 = 0. Let \u2208 (0, 1) be the constant saving rate and \u2208 (0, 1) the constant proportion of the capital stock that depreciates during production. From the identities ( ) = ( )+ ( )+ ( ) and ( ) = ( ), where ( ), ( ), and ( ) are consumption, saving, and investment, respectively, all evaluated at time , it follows that the equation of capital accumulation i\u1e61",
